node.text:
Thank you to all the lovely humans who participated in this video - you are wonderful and your support means the world.⁣⁣
⁣⁣
I’m really proud of this partnership with @MQmentalhealth and I hope in a small way this gives you an excuse to open up new conversations! ⁣⁣#findthelight 
⁣⁣
Sunglasses are back in stock and available now, exclusively from @baxterandbonny⁣⁣
⁣⁣
For competition terms go to: www.gemmastyles.com/ftlterms

node.text:
A scary post! I always feel like a fraud when I get those “drop the skincare routine” comments because honestly I’ve struggled A LOT with my skin. Eventually a few years ago I went on roaccutane (aka accutane or isotretinoin) which people always have a lot to say about… but for a couple of years it worked perfectly for me, until the summer of 2020 when spots started to return. I tried everything I could at home. And after months of pain and frustration, I ended up with quite a scary lump in my neck. Multiple hospital trips and even an MRI eventually suggested that my cystic acne was affecting my lymphatic system. That was the last straw and I hopped ASAP back on isotretinoin at the end of January. It’s been a long path and anyone who’s tried it knows it’s a serious undertaking — thanks to anyone who’s commented on the dry lips in my photos for the last eight months… I know, thanks. 😂⁣
⁣
Today is #acnepositivityday and I don’t know what I’m trying to say even? But when you’re struggling against your own face it so often feels like nobody else is, and also there’s no hope for it to change. I’ve posted on stories before with patches and spot cream etc on my face but, especially with the worst parts on the sides of my face, by the time I put makeup on you couldn’t usually see in a front-on picture, so I’m making space for spots on the grid! I am so so here for the incredible community on here that helps to normalise acne and other skin issues and make us realise that there’s nothing wrong with it, or wrong with us! But also we’re often made to feel like caring about your skin or spots is vain and silly and it’s just not. It can really affect mental health and self esteem, and medically even more for some of us! So if this makes anyone feel a touch less alone and a tad more hopeful, I hope I can do that much ♥️

node.text: OUT OF OFFICE (except I’m back now, hello) 🍃 As much as I nod my head when everyone else talks about the importance of rest… it had been a whiiiiile. A full week of switching off: no socials, outdoors, family, activities and all the food. Didn’t quite realise how much it was needed ♥️ Special mention to @swanhotelnewbybridge who we finally got to stay with for a couple of nights (and who also upgraded our room (ad!) so I got breakfast in bed plus a tv that appears as if from nowhere 🥲 which if you know me is a recipe for utter joy). And of course five stars to @michalmlynowski for being a 10/10 fun pal, kayaker, wasp shoo-er and 🪨solid in a crisis 🍀 Hope you’ve also been getting the rest you need lately xxx

node.text:
Scrubbed up for the @britishpodcastawards over the weekend! 🎧 Thanks so much to everyone who voted @goodinfluencegs into the Listeners’ Choice Top 10 — especially for a podcast less than a year old... me: THRILLED 🥲⁣
⁣
I was honoured to present the award for Best Wellbeing Podcast to @podcastpenny for @discoveringdementia ⭐️ ⁣
⁣
Can’t believe we’re 2/3 of the way through Season 2 of the podcast now! If you missed it, this week’s episode features @therealbenhurst on toxic masculinity and coming up next week: confidence with @calliethorpe! ⁣
⁣
📸 @milliewebber

node.text: Got to see my brilliant friend @charlycox1’s exhibition ‘Wish You Were Here’ today and this is an official PROUD POST ♥️ Also a reminder that the sentimental things you may have kept under your bed have significant artistic and emotional value. I know lots of people have gone to see it this week and she has raised lots of splendid cash for @mqmentalhealth and yes. GOOD THINGS. ARE GOOD.
